<br>
For most interplanetary velocities (ie 10-100 km/s) a chemical rocket can go as fast as a nucler propelled one, be it nuclear thermal, nuclear electric, or nuclear pulse. The main difference one will see is in the mass of the propellant, and hence the vehicle. For a spacecraft to follow the same trajectory and push the same payload, one powered by a chemical rocket would be almost twice as massive as one powered by a solid cored nuclear thermal rocket. This mass savings could be used to push more payload, or achieve a greater velocity by pushing less mass.<br>
<br>
Usualy comparisons are made through specific impulse (Isp), or how much thrust is gained from one pound of propellant for 1 sec. The highest Isp for a chemical rocket is 709s, but this uses complicated metalized fuel. H-LOx produces about 540s idealy, but most engines are far from ideal. A solid cored nuclear rocket can produce about 900-1000s, a gas cored nuclear rocket 2000-3000s, an ion engine about 8000-30000s, VASMIR 3000-30000s, and EPPP 2000-1000000s. The higher exaust velocities of most of these systems results in lower thrust outputs for engine weight (particularly in nuclear electric drives), but the fuel saved is more then worth it. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2403<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/12/02 1:29:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=183.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: How fast could a Nuclear Powered spacecraft go?</span><hr size=1> There was another thread on this. Went for miles and miles. The wafer Americium 242 engine might be fastest. 2 weeks to Mars. Depends on your definition of fastest. In a race, the winner might be decided by distance. In a race to Proxima Centaurii a light sail could eventually overtake the best nuclear drive. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=use