<br>
I would place the major blame on politics.  There doesn't seem<br>
to be any major theoretical problems and few engineering difficulties.<br>
<br>
I would say it's the limited test ban treaty that forbids above<br>
ground nuclear detonations that is one of the biggest hurdles...<br>
<br>
That and the PR problem of setting off 300 nukes in the biosphere in <br>
a matter of a few minutes.  Granted they would be of very tiny yields,<br>
but to the general public a nuke is a nuke.<br>
<br>
At the height of atmospheric nuclear testing it was estimated <br>
that a 4000 ton Orion launch would add an additional 1% to the world's<br>
radiation levels. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/13/02 11:11:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=183.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why havn't we built the Orion?</span><hr size=1> How much would it contribute now? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2442<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/14/02 1:14:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=183.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why havn't we built the Orion?</span><hr size=1> We have cleaner nukes now. Background levels of radiation have probably increased due to X ray diagnostics, transportation systems, engineering and other radioactive general technology. Uranium and Pluto are still in the atmosphere gradually raining down. A lot of it went very high and takes awhile to come down. Decay has diminished the radiation level of residual fallout. No fallout has been added since 63 I think. <br>
An Orion today would be much cleaner than the earlier versions. Bomb technology has advanced. I don't know if it would be a lot less fallout but I think it could be. Everything balanced out I think the level of residual radiation would be less than 1%. A single one of the large thermonuclear bombs tested in the early 60's would probably create a hundred times more radiation than Orion today. Back in the 50's and 60's they were detonating hundreds. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1468<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/14/02 8:49:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=183.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why havn't we built the Orion?</span><hr size=1> The estimate is that a 4000 ton Orion ground launched today with the cleanest nukes that have been developed (not theorized) would result in the statistical death of one random person world-wide.  Of course anti-nukers will say even one death is unacceptable.  Never mind that one launch could place the entire infrastructure in space to develop more Orions (off world).  People die on roller coasters every year.  I guess theme parks are more important to the future of mankind!<br>
