Has nothing to say against a space launch.<br>
 Every major Mars exploration proposal exept for Mars Direct (which doesn't seem to get taken seriously) involves several hundred tons in LEO to start. That's a 10 meter ship right there!<br>
<br>
Forget about ground launch! Unless you can come up with an absolute guarantee that there'll be <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">no</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> fallout, then hysteria will stop it from being more than an old wild idea from the bad old days when they were setting nukes off all the time.<br>
<br>
Separate the concept of Orion from the ground launch, and the reasons drop to near-zero. Add in the CDI's idea of a multinational mission burning off all the old warheads, and it's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>negative</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->! As in, there's not only no <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>good</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> reasons against it, but it's easily proven that all the &quot;reasons&quot; are bad -like it's a dodge by the Pentagon (also duping the UN, the Chinese &amp; Russians and every other nation involved), to make us all complacent to the idea of nuclear bomb powered lasers in orbit to read our minds and program us all to think like republicans! (or whatever the frell the GNAWaNPiS paranoia fantasy is).<br>
 Another popular one is that we'd be upsetting the delicate balance of the beautiful environment of the solar wind.<br>
Any others? (rant over)<br>
<br>
<br>
 Recall from the new book, that one real concern was test-ability of NPR. One misfire in a ground launch, and the mission is in danger, since it's going to fall! Space launch removes that, along with the uncertainty remaining about controlling the yield of a sub-kt bomb. The bombs for the 10 meter ship were all at least 2kt, right?<br>
 A space-use ship is entirely testable, in any increment from no pulses, to tiny pulses, to single full shots, to around the Moon &amp; back for a post-shakedown refit before loading for the real mission. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1475<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/14/02 1:04:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=183.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Why havn't we built the Orion?</span><hr size=1> Concerning the LTBT:<br>
